\begin_layout Standard
We assume spatial Lotka-Volterra dynamics.
 The average growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{i}$
\end_inset

 of a focus individual of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 then follows eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lv_individual"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\mu_{i}(r,t) & = & r_{i}+\beta_{ii}K_{ii}(r,t)C_{i}(t)+\beta_{io}\Sigma_{j\neq i}K_{ij}(r,t)C_{j}(t)\\
 & = & r_{i}+\beta_{ii}M_{ii}(r,t)+\beta_{io}M_{io}(r,t)
\end{array}\label{eq:lv_individual}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the intrinsic individual growth rate 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(and intrinsic per capita growth rate in a population model ?)
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{ii}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{io}$
\end_inset

 are individual-level interaction coefficients with a conspecific and a
 heterospecific, respectively.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}(t)K_{ij}(r,t)$
\end_inset

 is the expected number of organisms of heterospecifics around a typical
 organism of species 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 within a sphere of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 centered on the focal organism at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{ii}(r,t)=K_{ii}(r,t)C_{i}(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{io}(r,t)=\Sigma_{j\neq i}K_{ij}(r,t)C_{j}(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that we are close to an equilibrium at the local scale, and that
 intra- and interspecific interaction strengths are equal 
\shape italic
at the individual level
\shape default
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{ii}=\beta_{io}).$
\end_inset

 We can rewrite eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lv_individual"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r_{i}+\beta M_{ii}(r,t)+\beta M_{io}(r,t)\approx0\label{eq:lv_individual_equilibrium}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now focus on the population level.
 Lotka-Volterra dynamics translates into eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lv_population"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, assuming that all interspecific interactions are equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{io}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{1}{C_{i}}\frac{dC_{i}(r,t)}{dt} & = & r_{i}+\alpha_{ii}C_{i}(t)+\alpha_{io}C_{o}(t)\end{array}\approx0\label{eq:lv_population}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can therefore write 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ii}=\beta\frac{M_{ii}(r,t)}{C_{i}(t)C_{i}(t)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{io}=\beta\frac{M_{io}(r,t)}{C_{i}(t)C_{o}(t)}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do we write that because both are equal to 0?FB Nope - but the idea is,
 if we're close to equilibrium, the odds that a difference in model nonlineariti
es will make a big difference in model behaviour is low.
 I also made the same mistake as above when writing the alphas (I was missing
 a division by C_i since I initially multiplied by one C_i too many), but
 quite fortunately it cancelled out since there's C_i(t) in both denominators
 of the alphas.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{\alpha_{io}}{\alpha_{ii}} & = & \frac{M_{io}(r,t)}{M_{ii}(r,t)}\frac{C_{i}(t)}{C_{o}(t)}\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
D_{i}(r,t) & = & \frac{M_{ii}(r,t)}{M_{ii}(r,t)+M_{io}(r,t)}\\
\Leftrightarrow M_{io}(r,t) & = & \left(1-D_{i}(r,t)\right)M_{ii}(r,t)
\end{array}\label{eq:dominance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\alpha_{io}}{\alpha_{ii}}=\left(1-D_{i}(r,t)\right)\frac{C_{i}(t)}{C_{o}(t)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first focus on microphytoplankton (reasoning is the same for nanophytopla
nkton) in a 3-species community with even distribution of abundances.
 We know that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(r_{\text{threshold}})\approx0.4$
\end_inset

 at equilibrium.
 In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-D_{i}(r,t)\right)\frac{C_{i}(t)}{C_{o}(t)}=0.3$
\end_inset

.
 This is enough in a 3-species Lotka-Volterra model to maintain coexistence
 (simulations were done).
 The same applies for nanophytoplankton (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha_{io}}{\alpha_{ii}}\approx0.05$
\end_inset

), assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $D(r_{\text{threshold}})\approx0.9$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Notes on LV
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While trying to simulate a 3-species Lotka-Volterra model to ensure that
 the interaction strength ratios that we obtained allowed for coexistence,
 I stumbled into an odd behaviour (stability even when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}>1$
\end_inset

, as long as all 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are equal).
 In order to understand what happened, I switched to the simpler and well-known
 2-species LV.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
\frac{dN_{1}}{dt}= & N_{1}\left(r_{1}-\alpha_{11}N_{1}-\alpha_{12}N_{2}\right)\\
\frac{dN_{2}}{dt}= & N_{2}\left(r_{2}-\alpha_{22}N_{2}-\alpha_{21}N_{1}\right)
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's now assume 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}=r_{2}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ii}=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{12}=\alpha_{21}=\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 We look for a non-trivial equilibrium (
\begin_inset Formula $N_{1}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{2}\neq0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
N_{1}= & 1-\alpha N_{2}\\
N_{2}= & 1-\alpha N_{1}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Leftrightarrow\begin{cases}
N_{1}= & 1-\alpha N_{2}\\
N_{2}= & 1-\alpha(1-\alpha N_{2})
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Leftrightarrow\begin{cases}
N_{1}= & 1-\alpha N_{2}\\
N_{2}= & \frac{1-\alpha}{1-\alpha^{2}}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Leftrightarrow\begin{cases}
N_{1}= & 1-\frac{\alpha}{1+\alpha}\\
N_{2}= & \frac{1}{1+\alpha}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Leftrightarrow\begin{cases}
N_{1}= & \frac{1}{1+\alpha}\\
N_{2}= & \frac{1}{1+\alpha}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that we can reach an equilibrium with whatever values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, even those where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{11}\alpha_{22}<\alpha_{12}\alpha_{21}$
\end_inset

, which I could confirm by simulations, and which goes against what we know
 from the LV-model.
 This is a specific case of the LV model: when species are exactly identical
 with regards to their parameters, stability can emerge, but this corresponds
 to a structurally unstable system (Barabas et al.
 2016 â€“ this might need to be checked in a math-orientated textbook).
 Note that this does not apply anymore when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ij}\neq\alpha_{ji}$
\end_inset

 (or when 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}\neq r_{2}$
\end_inset

): in this case, there is coexistence when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{11}\alpha_{22}>\alpha_{12}\alpha_{21}$
\end_inset

, not when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{11}\alpha_{22}<\alpha_{12}\alpha_{21}$
\end_inset

 (see codes attached in the e-mail).
\end_layout

